---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { withBase } from '@/lib/withBase';
import PageHeader from '@/components/ui/PageHeader.astro';
import Callout from '@/components/ui/Callout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="The spoofing problem"
  description="Why open GNSS navigation data is forgeable, and what OSNMA does about it."
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="0 · Orientation"
    title="The spoofing problem"
    lead="A civil GNSS receiver believes whatever it decodes. OSNMA exists so it no longer has to."
  />

  <p>
    The Galileo Open Service broadcasts its navigation message in the clear. Any
    receiver can read the ephemeris, clock and timing data that let it compute a
    position — and so can anyone with a signal generator. Because the open message
    carries no built-in proof of origin, a receiver cannot, on its own, tell a
    genuine Galileo message from a counterfeit one.
  </p>

  <h2>Spoofing, meaconing, replay</h2>
  <p>
    Several attacks exploit that blind trust:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Spoofing</strong> — the attacker synthesises counterfeit signals with
      forged navigation data to push the receiver to a false position or time.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Meaconing</strong> — the attacker receives the real signals and
      re-broadcasts them, without necessarily decoding them, to mislead victims.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Replay</strong> — the attacker records authentic data and re-transmits
      it later, so the bits are real but the timing is a lie.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    These are not exotic: software-defined radios make convincing spoofing
    inexpensive, and the consequences — misdirected vehicles, falsified timestamps
    in finance and power grids — are serious.
  </p>

  <h2>What OSNMA provides</h2>
  <p>
    OSNMA adds <strong>authentication of the navigation message</strong>: data-origin
    authentication and integrity. A receiver that completes OSNMA verification knows
    the navigation data genuinely originated from Galileo and was not altered in
    flight. It achieves this by attaching short authentication tags (truncated MACs)
    to the data and disclosing the keys to check them a little later — the
    <a href={withBase('/foundations/tesla')}>TESLA</a> scheme.
  </p>

  <Callout type="security" title="What OSNMA is — and is not">
    <p>
      OSNMA authenticates the <em>navigation data message</em>. It does
      <strong>not</strong> encrypt the signal (the data stays public), it does
      <strong>not</strong> by itself authenticate the ranging code or defeat pure
      signal-replay at the physical layer (that is the domain of separate, often
      paid, services), and it is <strong>not</strong> instantaneous: because keys are
      disclosed with delay, authentication always carries some latency.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>The shape of the solution</h2>
  <p>
    Authenticating a public broadcast to millions of anonymous receivers is harder
    than it sounds. Digital signatures would work but are heavy for a trickle-rate
    data channel; symmetric MACs are light but seem to require sharing a secret with
    everyone — which would let anyone forge. OSNMA threads this needle with a
    delayed-disclosure key chain anchored by a signature and a Merkle tree. The rest
    of this guide builds that solution from the ground up.
  </p>

  <p>
    Next: the <a href={withBase('/foundations/crypto-primer')}>cryptographic toolkit</a> behind
    it, then <a href={withBase('/foundations/tesla')}>how TESLA turns delay into trust</a>.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
